'''New Cinema History''' is a movement of media historians dedicated to rewriting film history as a social history of film cultures, instead of merely an art history of the moving image. The term was coined by Richard Maltby as "a body of work that focuses on the circulation and consumption of film and examines cinema as a site of social and cultural exchange."<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/692084803|title=Explorations in new cinema history : approaches and case studies|last=1952-|first=Maltby, Richard,|last2=1962-|first2=Biltereyst, Daniël,|last3=Philippe.|first3=Meers,|date=2011|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|year=|isbn=9781405199490|location=|pages=xii|oclc=692084803}}</ref> Maltby's terminology partly aimed to institutionalize and expand to an international scale his prior decade-long collaboration with Melvyn Stokes researching Hollywood film audiences,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/41338511|title=Identifying Hollywood's audiences : cultural identity and the movies|last=Melvyn.|first=Stokes,|last2=1952-|first2=Maltby, Richard,|date=1999|publisher=British Film Institute|isbn=9780851707389|oclc=41338511}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/45306616|title=Hollywood spectatorship : changing perceptions of cinema audiences|last=Melvyn.|first=Stokes,|last2=1952-|first2=Maltby, Richard,|date=2001|publisher=BFI Pub|isbn=9780851708119|oclc=45306616}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/180880538|title=Going to the movies : Hollywood and the social experience of cinema|last=1952-|first=Maltby, Richard,|last2=Melvyn.|first2=Stokes,|last3=1950-|first3=Allen, Robert Clyde,|date=2007|publisher=University of Exeter Press|isbn=9780859898119|oclc=180880538}}</ref> and coincided with the formation of the HoMER Network: History of Moviegoing, Exhibition and Reception.
